## Why This Is Asked
Tests a beginner-friendly, practical approach to a real-time chat path at scale, focusing on end-to-end latency and bottleneck isolation without production changes. It validates data modeling, load shaping, and tooling choice under realistic constraints.

## Key Concepts
- Load stages: ramp, sustain, ramp-down
- Metrics: p95/p99 latency, throughput, error rate, resource usage
- Data strategy: synthetic users and room IDs for realistic contention
- Isolation: run API, DB, and auth tests separately to localize bottlenecks
- Tooling: JS-friendly load testing (k6) for quick ramp-up and clear metrics

## Code Example
```javascript
import http from 'k6/http';
import { check, sleep } from 'k6';
export const options = {
  stages: [
    { duration: '10m', target: 8000 },
    { duration: '2m', target: 8000 },
    { duration: '2m', target: 0 }
  ]
};
export default function () {
  const payload = JSON.stringify({ roomId: 'room-A', userId: `user_${__VU}`, text: 'hello' });
  const res = http.post('https://api.example.com/messages', payload, {
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' }
  });
  check(res, { 'status 200': r => r.status === 200 });
  sleep(0.08);
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you adjust the plan if messages were delivered via WebSocket instead of HTTP REST?
- What additional metrics would you collect to distinguish client vs server-side latency?

## Why This Is Asked
This question evaluates the ability to design comprehensive performance testing for a complex, multi-component real-time system. It tests understanding of end-to-end latency measurement across distributed components, resilience testing with external dependencies, and validation of autoscaling behavior under variable load conditions.

## Key Concepts
- WebSocket connection scalability and lifecycle management
- Kafka throughput optimization, topic partitioning strategies, and consumer lag monitoring
- Redis data access patterns for presence tracking and rate limiting implementations
- Backpressure mechanisms and circuit breaker patterns for fault tolerance
- Autoscaling trigger configuration and failover strategies for external gateway dependencies

## Code Example
```javascript
import ws from 'k6/ws';
import http from 'k6/http';
import { check } from 'k6';

export const options = {
  stages: [
    { duration: '2m', target: 30000 },
    { duration: '5m', target: 60000 },
    { duration: '2m', target: 100000 },
  ],
};

export default function () {
  const url = __ENV.WS_URL;
  const response = ws.connect(url, {}, function (socket) {
    socket.on('open', () => {
      console.log('Connected');
    });

    socket.on('message', (message) => {
      const latency = Date.now() - JSON.parse(message).timestamp;
      check(latency, {
        'latency < 120ms': latency < 120,
      });
    });
  });

  check(response, { 'status is 101': (r) => r && r.status === 101 });
}
```

## Test Execution Strategy
Implement gradual load ramping to validate autoscaling triggers, inject fault scenarios to test circuit breaker functionality, and simulate external gateway outages to verify failover mechanisms. Monitor system-wide metrics to ensure performance targets are met under various conditions.

